{{multiple issues| {{Underlinked|date=March 2014}} {{Orphan|date=March 2014}} }}
A '''social edition''' is a form of textual scholarship that utilizes social media like Wikimedia or blogs to create annotated editions of texts. [[Constance Crompton|Crompton]], [[Alyssa Arbuckle|Arbuckle]] and [[Ray Siemens|Siemens]] describe that "Using social media allows us to integrate a new stage into the editorial process — a stage that fills the gap between an edition’s initial planning stages and its concluding blind peer review, which capitalizes on the engaged knowledge communities inside and outside the academy".<ref>[http://src-online.ca/index.php/src/article/viewFile/118/268 "Understanding the Social Edition Through Iterative Implementation: The Case of the Devonshire MS (BL Add MS 17492),"] with Constance Crompton, Alyssa Arbuckle, and the Devonshire MS Editorial Group. ''Scholarly and Research Communication'' 4.2 (2013). 9 pp.</ref>
== List of social editions ==
=== Open participation === Participation is open to registered and unregistered contributors. * [[:wikisource:The Annotated The Tales of John Oliver Hobbes|The Annotated ''The Tales of John Oliver Hobbes'']] * [[:wikibooks:The Devonshire Manuscript|A Social Edition of the Devonshire MS]]
=== Semi-open participation === Participation is allowed through a process of review by the project members. * [http://www.futureofthebook.org/iraqreport/ The Iraq Study Group Report]
